In this update:
Africa
[1] Cholera - Mozambique (Sofala)
[2) Cholera - Congo DR (South Kivu)

******
[1] Cholera - Mozambique (Sofala)
Date: Mon 11 Oct 2021
Source: CM Journal [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://www.cmjornal.pt/mundo/africa/detalhe/surto-de-colera-provoca-160-casos-em-mocambique?ref=Cidades_CmaoMinuto


Mozambican health authorities announced this Monday [11 Oct 2021] an outbreak of cholera in the district of Caia, Sofala province, in the center of the country. The outbreak has already caused 160 cases with no deaths recorded.

The first suspicions arose in late August [2021], but have been confirmed through laboratory tests, Justino Antonio, district director of health services in Caia told Radio Mozambique.

A team of technicians from the provincial health department is investigating the origin of the outbreak, which only occurs at the district headquarters, while local services have installed tents to treat the sick. "We have 3 tents installed, one for more serious cases," explained the person in charge. At the same time, there is distribution of products for water treatment and awareness of the use of latrines.

--
Communicated by:
Mahmoud Orabi
<ahstandards@gmail.com>

[Sofala province is in central Mozambique, not adjacent to Capo Delgado where cholera has also been reported. - Mod.LL]

******
[2) Cholera - Congo DR (South Kivu)
Date: Mon 11 Oct 2021
Source: 7sur7 [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://7sur7.cd/2021/10/11/sud-kivu-pres-de-200-cas-de-cholera-dont-13-deces-enregistres-kitutu


In total, 199 cases of cholera have already been recorded in the Kitutu health zone in Mwenga territory in South Kivu, since July [2021].

Among these cases, 13 deaths have already been recorded in this part of the province.

In a press briefing held on [Sat 9 Oct 2021] in his office, Robert Masine Kinenwa, provincial minister of health, indicated that water pollution is at the base of this outbreak of cholera cases in this part of the country. He stated that several other patients are currently being observed in health facilities.

--
Communicated by:
Mahmoud Orabi
<ahstandards@gmail.com>

[ProMED thanks Mahmoud Orabi for submitting this report. - Mod.LL

